Counters
========

   Everything LaTeX numbers for you has a counter associated with it.
The name of the counter is the same as the name of the environment or
command that produces the number, except with no @{b}\ @{ub}. (enumi - enumiv
are used for the nested enumerate environment.) Below is a list of the
counters used in LaTeX's standard document styles to control numbering.

      part            paragraph       figure          enumi
      chapter         subparagraph    table           enumii
      section         page            footnote        enumiii
      subsection      equation        mpfootnote      enumiv
      subsubsection


 @{" \addtocounter " Link "\addtocounter"} 
 @{" \alph " Link "\alph"} 
 @{" \arabic " Link "\arabic"} 
 @{" \fnsymbol " Link "\fnsymbol"} 
 @{" \newcounter " Link "\newcounter"} 
 @{" \roman " Link "\roman"} 
 @{" \setcounter " Link "\setcounter"} 
 @{" \usecounter " Link "\usecounter"} 
 @{" \value " Link "\value"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\addtocounter" "latex.guide/\addtocounter"
@Next "\alph"
@Prev "Counters"
@Toc "Counters"

\addtocounter
-------------

   @{b}\addtocounter{counter}{value}@{ub}

   The @{b}\addtocounter@{ub} command increments the @{b}counter@{ub} by the amount
specified by the @{b}value@{ub} argument.  The @{b}value@{ub} argument can be negative.


@EndNode

@Node "\alph" "latex.guide/\alph"
@Next "\arabic"
@Prev "\addtocounter"
@Toc "Counters"

\alph
-----

   @{b}\alph{counter}@{ub}

   This command causes the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} to be printed in
alphabetic characters.  The @{b}\alph@{ub} command causes lower case alphabetic
alphabetic characters, i.e., @{b}a, b, c...@{ub} while the @{b}\Alph@{ub} command causes
upper case alphabetic characters, i.e., @{b}A, B, C...@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\arabic" "latex.guide/\arabic"
@Next "\fnsymbol"
@Prev "\alph"
@Toc "Counters"

\arabic
-------

   @{b}\arabic{counter}@{ub}

   The @{b}\arabic@{ub} command causes the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} to be printed in
arabic numbers, i.e., @{b}3@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\fnsymbol" "latex.guide/\fnsymbol"
@Next "\newcounter"
@Prev "\arabic"
@Toc "Counters"

\fnsymbol
---------

   @{b}\fnsymbol{counter}@{ub}

   The @{b}\fnsymbol@{ub} command causes the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} to be printed
in a specific sequence of nine symbols that can be used for numbering
footnotes.

   NB. @{b}counter@{ub} must have a value between 1 and 9 inclusive.


@EndNode

@Node "\newcounter" "latex.guide/\newcounter"
@Next "\roman"
@Prev "\fnsymbol"
@Toc "Counters"

\newcounter
-----------

   @{b}\newcounter{foo}[counter]@{ub}

   The @{b}\newcounter@{ub} command defines a new counter named @{b}foo@{ub}.  The
optional argument @{b}[counter]@{ub} causes the counter @{b}foo@{ub} to be reset whenever
the counter named in the optional argument is incremented.


@EndNode

@Node "\roman" "latex.guide/\roman"
@Next "\setcounter"
@Prev "\newcounter"
@Toc "Counters"

\roman
------

   @{b}\roman{counter}@{ub}

   This command causes the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} to be printed in roman
numerals.  The @{b}\roman@{ub} command causes lower case roman numerals, i.e.,
@{b}i, ii, iii...@{ub}, while the @{b}\Roman@{ub} command causes upper case roman
numerals, i.e., @{b}I, II, III...@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\setcounter" "latex.guide/\setcounter"
@Next "\usecounter"
@Prev "\roman"
@Toc "Counters"

\setcounter
-----------

   @{b}\setcounter{counter}{value}@{ub}

   The @{b}\setcounter@{ub} command sets the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} to that
specified by the @{b}value@{ub} argument.


@EndNode

@Node "\usecounter" "latex.guide/\usecounter"
@Next "\value"
@Prev "\setcounter"
@Toc "Counters"

\usecounter
-----------

   @{b}\usecounter{counter}@{ub}

   The @{b}\usecounter@{ub} command is used in the second argument of the @{b}list@{ub}
environment to allow the counter specified to be used to number the
list items.


@EndNode

@Node "\value" "latex.guide/\value"
@Next "Cross References"
@Prev "\usecounter"
@Toc "Counters"

\value
------

   @{b}\value{counter}@{ub}

   The @{b}\value@{ub} command produces the value of the @{b}counter@{ub} named in the
mandatory argument.  It can be used where LaTeX expects an integer or
number, such as the second argument of a @{b}\setcounter@{ub} or @{b}\addtocounter@{ub}
command, or in:

             \hspace{\value{foo}\parindent}

   It is useful for doing arithmetic with counters.


@EndNode

@Node "Cross References" "latex.guide/Cross References"
@Next "\label"
@Prev "\value"
@Toc "Commands"

Cross References
================

   One reason for numbering things like figures and equations is to
refer the reader to them, as in "See Figure 3 for more details."


 @{" \label " Link "\label"} 
 @{" \pageref " Link "\pageref"} 
 @{" \ref " Link "\ref"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\label" "latex.guide/\label"
@Next "\pageref"
@Prev "Cross References"
@Toc "Cross References"

\label
------

   @{b}\label{key}@{ub}

   A @{b}\label@{ub} command appearing in ordinary text assigns to the @{b}key@{ub} the
number of the current sectional unit; one appearing inside a numbered
environment assigns that number to the @{b}key@{ub}.

   A @{b}key@{ub} can consist of any sequence of letters, digits, or punctuation
characters.  Upper and lowercase letters are different.


@EndNode

@Node "\pageref" "latex.guide/\pageref"
@Next "\ref"
@Prev "\label"
@Toc "Cross References"

\pageref
--------

   @{b}\pageref{key}@{ub}

   The @{b}\pageref@{ub} command produces the page number of the place in the
text where the corresponding @{b}\label@{ub} command appears. ie. where
@{b}\label{key}@{ub} appears.


@EndNode

@Node "\ref" "latex.guide/\ref"
@Next "Definitions"
@Prev "\pageref"
@Toc "Cross References"

\ref
----

   @{b}\ref{key}@{ub}

   The @{b}\ref@{ub} command produces the number of the sectional unit, equation
number, ... of the corresponding @{b}\label@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "Definitions" "latex.guide/Definitions"
@Next "\newcommand"
@Prev "\ref"
@Toc "Commands"

Definitions
===========


 @{" \newcommand " Link "\newcommand"} 
 @{" \newenvironment " Link "\newenvironment"} 
 @{" \newtheorem " Link "\newtheorem"} 
 @{" \newfont " Link "\newfont"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\newcommand" "latex.guide/\newcommand"
@Next "\newenvironment"
@Prev "Definitions"
@Toc "Definitions"

\newcommand
-----------

      \newcommand{cmd}[args]{def}
      \renewcommand{cmd}[args]{def}

   These commands define (or redefine) a command.

@{b}cmd@{ub}
     A command name beginning with a @{b}\ @{ub}.  For @{b}\newcommand@{ub} it must not
     be already defined and must not begin with @{b}\end@{ub}; for @{b}\renewcommand@{ub}
     it must already be defined.

@{b}args@{ub}
     An integer from 1 to 9 denoting the number of arguments of the
     command being defined.  The default is for the command to have no
     arguments.

@{b}def@{ub}
     The text to be substituted for every occurrence of @{b}cmd@{ub}; a
     parameter of the form @{b}#n@{ub} in @{b}cmd@{ub} is replaced by the text of the nth
     argument when this substitution takes place.


@EndNode

@Node "\newenvironment" "latex.guide/\newenvironment"
@Next "\newtheorem"
@Prev "\newcommand"
@Toc "Definitions"

\newenvironment
---------------

      \newenvironment{nam}[args]{begdef}{enddef}
      \renewenvironment{nam}[args]{begdef}{enddef}

   These commands define or redefine an environment.

@{b}nam@{ub}
     The name of the environment.  For @{b}\newenvironment@{ub} there must be no
     currently defined environment by that name, and the command @{b}\nam@{ub}
     must be undefined.  For @{b}\renewenvironment@{ub} the environment must
     already be defined.

@{b}args@{ub}
     An integer from 1 to 9 denoting the number of arguments of the
     newly-defined environment.  The default is no arguments.

@{b}begdef@{ub}
     The text substituted for every occurrence of @{b}\begin{nam}@{ub}; a
     parameter of the form @{b}#n@{ub} in @{b}cmd@{ub} is replaced by the text of the nth
     argument when this substitution takes place.

@{b}enddef@{ub}
     The text substituted for every occurrence of @{b}\end{nam}@{ub}.  It may
     not contain any argument parameters.


@EndNode

@Node "\newtheorem" "latex.guide/\newtheorem"
@Next "\newfont"
@Prev "\newenvironment"
@Toc "Definitions"

\newtheorem
-----------

      \newtheorem{env_name}{caption}[within]
      \newtheorem{env_name}[numbered_like]{caption}

   This command defines a theorem-like environment.

@{b}env_name@{ub}
     The name of the environment to be defined. A string of letters.
     It must not be the name of an existing environment or counter.

@{b}caption@{ub}
     The text printed at the beginning of the environment, right before
     the number. This may simply say "Theorem", for example.

@{b}within@{ub}
     The name of an already defined counter, usually of a sectional
     unit.  Provides a means of resetting the new theorem counter @{i}within@{ui}
     the sectional unit.

@{b}numbered_like@{ub}
     The name of an already defined theorem-like environment.

   The @{b}\newtheorem@{ub} command may have at most one optional argument.


@EndNode

@Node "\newfont" "latex.guide/\newfont"
@Next "Document Styles"
@Prev "\newtheorem"
@Toc "Definitions"

\newfont
--------

   @{b}\newfont{cmd}{font_name}@{ub}

   Defines the command name @{b}cmd@{ub}, which must not be currently defined,
to be a declaration that selects the font named @{b}font_name@{ub} to be the
current font.


@EndNode

@Node "Document Styles" "latex.guide/Document Styles"
@Next "\flushbottom"
@Prev "\newfont"
@Toc "Commands"

Document Styles
===============

   Valid LaTeX document styles include:

   @{b}*@{ub} article

   @{b}*@{ub} report

   @{b}*@{ub} letter

   @{b}*@{ub} book

   Other document styles are often available. See @{"Overview" Link "Overview"}, for details.
They are selected with the following command:

   @{b}\documentstyle [options] {style}@{ub}

   The options for the different styles are:

  1.     @{b}article@{ub} - 11pt, 12pt, twoside, twocolumn, draft, fleqn, leqno,
     acm

  2.     @{b}report@{ub}  - 11pt, 12pt, twoside, twocolumn, draft, fleqn, leqno,
     acm

  3.     @{b}letter@{ub}  - 11pt, 12pt, fleqn,   leqno, acm

  4.     @{b}book@{ub}    - 11pt, 12pt, twoside, twocolumn, draft, fleqn, leqno

   If you specify more than one option, they must be separated by a
comma.


 @{" \flushbottom " Link "\flushbottom"} 
 @{" \onecolumn " Link "\onecolumn"} 
 @{" \raggedbottom " Link "\raggedbottom"} 
 @{" \twocolumn " Link "\twocolumn"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\flushbottom" "latex.guide/\flushbottom"
@Next "\onecolumn"
@Prev "Document Styles"
@Toc "Document Styles"

\flushbottom
------------

   The @{b}\flushbottom@{ub} declaration makes all text pages the same height,
adding extra vertical space when necessary to fill out the page.

   This is the standard for the book style.


@EndNode

@Node "\onecolumn" "latex.guide/\onecolumn"
@Next "\raggedbottom"
@Prev "\flushbottom"
@Toc "Document Styles"

\onecolumn
----------

   The @{b}\onecolumn@{ub} declaration starts a new page and produces
single-column output.


@EndNode

@Node "\raggedbottom" "latex.guide/\raggedbottom"
@Next "\twocolumn"
@Prev "\onecolumn"
@Toc "Document Styles"

\raggedbottom
-------------

   The @{b}\raggedbottom@{ub} declaration makes all pages the height of the text
on that page.  No extra vertical space is added.


@EndNode

@Node "\twocolumn" "latex.guide/\twocolumn"
@Next "Environments"
@Prev "\raggedbottom"
@Toc "Document Styles"

\twocolumn
----------

   The @{b}\twocolumn@{ub} declaration starts a new page and produces two-column
output.


@EndNode

@Node "Environments" "latex.guide/Environments"
@Next "array"
@Prev "\twocolumn"
@Toc "Commands"

Environments
============

   LaTeX provides a number of different paragraph-making environments.
Each environment begins and ends in the same manner.

             \begin{environment-name}
             .
             .
             .
             \end{environment-name}


 @{" array " Link "array"} 
 @{" center " Link "center"} 
 @{" description " Link "description"} 
 @{" enumerate " Link "enumerate"} 
 @{" eqnarray " Link "eqnarray"} 
 @{" equation " Link "equation"} 
 @{" figure " Link "figure"} 
 @{" flushleft " Link "flushleft"} 
 @{" flushright " Link "flushright"} 
 @{" itemize " Link "itemize"} 
 @{" list " Link "list"} 
 @{" minipage " Link "minipage"} 
 @{" picture " Link "picture"} 
 @{" quotation " Link "quotation"} 
 @{" quote " Link "quote"} 
 @{" tabbing " Link "tabbing"} 
 @{" table " Link "table"} 
 @{" tabular " Link "tabular"} 
 @{" thebibliography " Link "thebibliography"} 
 @{" theorem " Link "theorem"} 
 @{" titlepage " Link "titlepage"} 
 @{" verbatim " Link "verbatim"} 
 @{" verse " Link "verse"} 


@EndNode

@Node "array" "latex.guide/array"
@Next "center"
@Prev "Environments"
@Toc "Environments"

array
-----

     \begin{array}{col1col2...coln}
     column 1 entry & column 2 entry ... & column n entry \\
      .
      .
      .
     \end{array}

   Math arrays are produced with the array environment.  It has a single
mandatory argument describing the number of columns and the alignment
within them.  Each column, @{b}coln@{ub}, is specified by a single letter that
tells how items in that row should be formatted.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}c@{ub} - for centred

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - for flushleft

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - for flushright

   Column entries must be separated by an @{b}&@{ub}.  Column entries may
include other LaTeX commands.  Each row of the array must be terminated
with the string @{b}\\ @{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "center" "latex.guide/center"
@Next "\centering"
@Prev "array"
@Toc "Environments"

center
------

      \begin{center}
      Text on line 1 \\
      Text on line 2 \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{center}

   The @{b}center@{ub} environment allows you to create a paragraph consisting of
lines that are centred within the left and right margins on the current
page.  Each line must be terminated with the string @{b}\\ @{ub}.


 @{" \centering " Link "\centering"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\centering" "latex.guide/\centering"
@Next "description"
@Prev "center"
@Toc "center"

\centering
..........

   This declaration corresponds to the @{b}center@{ub} environment.  This
declaration can be used inside an environment such as @{b}quote@{ub} or in a
@{b}parbox@{ub}.  The text of a figure or table can be centered on the page by
putting a @{b}\centering@{ub} command at the beginning of the figure or table
environment.

   Unlike the @{b}center@{ub} environment, the @{b}\centering@{ub} command does not start
a new paragraph; it simply changes how LaTeX formats paragraph units.
To affect a paragraph unit's format, the scope of the declaration must
contain the blank line or @{b}\end@{ub} command (of an environment like quote)
that ends the paragraph unit.


@EndNode

@Node "description" "latex.guide/description"
@Next "enumerate"
@Prev "\centering"
@Toc "Environments"

description
-----------

      \begin{description}
      \item [label] First item
      \item [label] Second item
      .
      .
      .
      \end{description}

   The @{b}description@{ub} environment is used to make labelled lists.  The
@{b}label@{ub} is bold face and flushed right.


@EndNode

@Node "enumerate" "latex.guide/enumerate"
@Next "eqnarray"
@Prev "description"
@Toc "Environments"

enumerate
---------

      \begin{enumerate}
      \item First item
      \item Second item
      .
      .
      .
      \end{enumerate}

   The @{b}enumerate@{ub} environment produces a numbered list.  Enumerations
can be nested within one another, up to four levels deep.  They can also
be nested within other paragraph-making environments.

   Each item of an enumerated list begins with an @{b}\item@{ub} command.  There
must be at least one @{b}\item@{ub} command within the environment.


@EndNode

@Node "eqnarray" "latex.guide/eqnarray"
@Next "equation"
@Prev "enumerate"
@Toc "Environments"

eqnarray
--------

      \begin{eqnarray}
      math formula 1 \\
      math formula 2 \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{eqnarray}

   The @{b}eqnarray@{ub} environment is used to display a sequence of equations
or inequalities.  It is very much like a three-column @{b}array@{ub}
environment, with consecutive rows separated by @{b}\\ @{ub} and consecutive
items within a row separated by an @{b}&@{ub}.  An equation number is placed on
every line unless that line has a @{b}\nonumber@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "equation" "latex.guide/equation"
@Next "figure"
@Prev "eqnarray"
@Toc "Environments"

equation
--------

      \begin{equation}
       math formula
      \end{equation}

   The @{b}equation@{ub} environment centres your equation on the page and places
the equation number in the right margin.


@EndNode

@Node "figure" "latex.guide/figure"
@Next "flushleft"
@Prev "equation"
@Toc "Environments"

figure
------

      \begin{figure}[placement]
     
       body of the figure
     
      \caption{figure title}
      \end{figure}

   Figures are objects that are not part of the normal text, and are
usually "floated" to a convenient place, like the top of a page.
Figures will not be split between two pages.

   The optional argument @{b}[placement]@{ub} determines where LaTeX will try to
place your figure.  There are four places where LaTeX can possibly put
a float:

  1.     @{b}h@{ub} (Here) - at the position in the text where the figure
     environment appears.

  2.     @{b}t@{ub} (Top) - at the top of a text page.

  3.     @{b}b@{ub} (Bottom) - at the bottom of a text page.

  4.     @{b}p@{ub} (Page of floats) - on a separate float page, which is a page
     containing no text, only floats.

   The standard report and article styles use the default placement @{b}tbp@{ub}.

   The body of the figure is made up of whatever text, LaTeX commands,
etc.  you wish.  The @{b}\caption@{ub} command allows you to title your figure.


@EndNode

@Node "flushleft" "latex.guide/flushleft"
@Next "\raggedright"
@Prev "figure"
@Toc "Environments"

flushleft
---------

      \begin{flushleft}
      Text on line 1 \\
      Text on line 2 \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{flushleft}

   The @{b}flushleft@{ub} environment allows you to create a paragraph
consisting of lines that are flushed left, to the left-hand margin.
Each line must be terminated with the string @{b}\\ @{ub}.


 @{" \raggedright " Link "\raggedright"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\raggedright" "latex.guide/\raggedright"
@Next "flushright"
@Prev "flushleft"
@Toc "flushleft"

\raggedright
............

   This declaration corresponds to the @{b}flushleft@{ub} environment.  This
declaration can be used inside an environment such as @{b}quote@{ub} or in a
@{b}parbox@{ub}.

   Unlike the @{b}flushleft@{ub} environment, the @{b}\raggedright@{ub} command does not
start a new paragraph; it simply changes how LaTeX formats paragraph
units.  To affect a paragraph unit's format, the scope of the
declaration must contain the blank line or @{b}\end@{ub} command (of an
environment like quote) that ends the paragraph unit.


@EndNode

@Node "flushright" "latex.guide/flushright"
@Next "\raggedleft"
@Prev "\raggedright"
@Toc "Environments"

flushright
----------

      \begin{flushright}
      Text on line 1 \\
      Text on line 2 \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{flushright}

   The @{b}flushright@{ub} environment allows you to create a paragraph
consisting of lines that are flushed right, to the right-hand margin.
Each line must be terminated with the string @{b}\\ @{ub}.


 @{" \raggedleft " Link "\raggedleft"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\raggedleft" "latex.guide/\raggedleft"
@Next "itemize"
@Prev "flushright"
@Toc "flushright"

\raggedleft
...........

   This declaration corresponds to the @{b}flushright@{ub} environment.  This
declaration can be used inside an environment such as @{b}quote@{ub} or in a
@{b}parbox@{ub}.

   Unlike the @{b}flushright@{ub} environment, the @{b}\raggedleft@{ub} command does not
start a new paragraph; it simply changes how LaTeX formats paragraph
units.  To affect a paragraph unit's format, the scope of the
declaration must contain the blank line or @{b}\end@{ub} command (of an
environment like quote) that ends the paragraph unit.


@EndNode

@Node "itemize" "latex.guide/itemize"
@Next "list"
@Prev "\raggedleft"
@Toc "Environments"

itemize
-------

      \begin{itemize}
      \item First item
      \item Second item
      .
      .
      .
      \end{itemize}

   The @{b}itemize@{ub} environment produces a "bulleted" list.  Itemizations
can be nested within one another, up to four levels deep.  They can also
be nested within other paragraph-making environments.

   Each item of an @{b}itemized@{ub} list begins with an @{b}\item@{ub} command.  There
must be at least one @{b}\item@{ub} command within the environment.


@EndNode

@Node "list" "latex.guide/list"
@Next "minipage"
@Prev "itemize"
@Toc "Environments"

list
----

      \begin{list}{label}{spacing}
      \item First item
      \item Second item
      .
      .
      .
      \end{list}

   The @{b}{label}@{ub} argument specifies how items should be labelled.  This
argument is a piece of text that is inserted in a box to form the
label.  This argument can and usually does contain other LaTeX commands.

   The @{b}{spacing}@{ub} argument contains commands to change the spacing
parameters for the list.  This argument will most often be null, i.e.,
@{b}{}@{ub}.  This will select all default spacing which should suffice for most
cases.


@EndNode

@Node "minipage" "latex.guide/minipage"
@Next "picture"
@Prev "list"
@Toc "Environments"

minipage
--------

      \begin{minipage}[position]{width}
       text
      \end{minipage}

   The @{b}minipage@{ub} environment is similar to a @{b}\parbox@{ub} command.  It takes
the same optional @{b}position@{ub} argument and mandatory @{b}width@{ub} argument.  You
may use other paragraph-making environments inside a minipage.

   Footnotes in a @{b}minipage@{ub} environment are handled in a way that is
particularly useful for putting footnotes in figures or tables.  A
@{b}\footnote@{ub} or @{b}\footnotetext@{ub} command puts the footnote at the bottom of
the minipage instead of at the bottom of the page, and it uses the
@{b}mpfootnote@{ub} counter instead of the ordinary @{b}footnote@{ub} counter.

   NOTE: Don't put one minipage inside another if you are using
footnotes; they may wind up at the bottom of the wrong minipage.


@EndNode

@Node "picture" "latex.guide/picture"
@Next "\circle"
@Prev "minipage"
@Toc "Environments"

picture
-------

      \begin{picture}(width,height)(x offset,y offset)
      .
       picture commands
      .
      \end{picture}

   The @{b}picture@{ub} environment allows you to create just about any kind of
picture you want containing text, lines, arrows and circles.  You tell
LaTeX where to put things in the picture by specifying their
coordinates.  A coordinate is a number that may have a decimal point and
a minus sign - a number like @{b}5@{ub}, @{b}2.3@{ub} or @{b}-3.1416@{ub}.  A coordinate specifies
a length in multiples of the unit length @{b}\unitlength@{ub}, so if @{b}\unitlength@{ub}
has been set to @{b}1cm@{ub}, then the coordinate 2.54 specifies a length of
2.54 centimeters.  You can change the value of @{b}\unitlength@{ub} anywhere you
want, using the @{b}\setlength@{ub} command, but strange things will happen if
you try changing it inside the picture environment.

   A position is a pair of coordinates, such as @{b}(2.4,-5)@{ub}, specifying
the point with x-coordinate @{b}2.4@{ub} and y-coordinate @{b}-5@{ub}.  Coordinates are
specified in the usual way with respect to an origin, which is normally
at the lower-left corner of the picture.  Note that when a position
appears as an argument, it is not enclosed in braces; the parentheses
serve to delimit the argument.

   The @{b}picture@{ub} environment has one mandatory argument, which is a
@{b}position@{ub}.  It specifies the size of the picture.  The environment
produces a rectangular box with width and height determined by this
argument's x- and y-coordinates.

   The @{b}picture@{ub} environment also has an optional @{b}position@{ub} argument,
following the @{b}size@{ub} argument, that can change the origin.  (Unlike
ordinary optional arguments, this argument is not contained in square
brackets.) The optional argument gives the coordinates of the point at
the lower-left corner of the picture (thereby determining the origin).
For example, if @{b}\unitlength@{ub} has been set to @{b}1mm@{ub}, the command...
        \begin{picture}(100,200)(10,20)
   ...produces a picture of width 100 millimeters and height 200
millimeters, whose lower-left corner is the point (10,20) and whose
upper-right corner is therefore the point (110,220).  When you first
draw a picture, you will omit the optional argument, leaving the origin
at the lower-left corner.  If you then want to modify your picture by
shifting everything, you just add the appropriate optional argument.

   The environment's mandatory argument determines the nominal size of
the picture.  This need bear no relation to how large the picture
really is; LaTeX will happily allow you to put things outside the
picture, or even off the page.  The picture's nominal size is used by
TeX in determining how much room to leave for it.

   Everything that appears in a picture is drawn by the @{b}\put@{ub} command.
The command...
        \put (11.3,-.3){...}
   ...puts the object specified by @{b}...@{ub} in the picture, with its
reference point at coordinates (11.3,-.3).  The reference points for
various objects will be described below.

   The @{b}\put@{ub} command creates an @{b}LR box@{ub}.  You can put anything in the
text argument of the @{b}\put@{ub} command that you'd put into the argument of
an @{b}\mbox@{ub} and related commands.  When you do this, the reference point
will be the lower left corner of the box.


 @{" \circle " Link "\circle"} 
 @{" \dashbox " Link "\dashbox"} 
 @{" \frame " Link "\frame"} 
 @{" \framebox (picture) " Link "\framebox (picture)"} 
 @{" \line " Link "\line"} 
 @{" \linethickness " Link "\linethickness"} 
 @{" \makebox (picture) " Link "\makebox (picture)"} 
 @{" \multiput " Link "\multiput"} 
 @{" \oval " Link "\oval"} 
 @{" \put " Link "\put"} 
 @{" \shortstack " Link "\shortstack"} 
 @{" \vector " Link "\vector"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\circle" "latex.guide/\circle"
@Next "\dashbox"
@Prev "picture"
@Toc "picture"

\circle
.......

   @{b}\circle[*]{diameter}@{ub}

   The @{b}\circle@{ub} command produces a circle of the specified diameter.  If
the @{b}*@{ub}-form of the command is used, LaTeX draws a solid circle.


@EndNode

@Node "\dashbox" "latex.guide/\dashbox"
@Next "\frame"
@Prev "\circle"
@Toc "picture"

\dashbox
........

   @{b}\dashbox{dash_length}(width,height){...}@{ub}

   The @{b}\dashbox@{ub} has an extra argument which specifies the width of each
dash.  A dashed box looks best when the @{b}width@{ub} and @{b}height@{ub} are multiples
of the @{b}dash_length@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\frame" "latex.guide/\frame"
@Next "\framebox (picture)"
@Prev "\dashbox"
@Toc "picture"

\frame
......

   @{b}\frame{...}@{ub}

   The @{b}\frame@{ub} command puts a rectangular frame around the object
specified in the argument.  The reference point is the bottom left
corner of the frame.  No extra space is put between the frame and the
object.


@EndNode

@Node "\framebox (picture)" "latex.guide/\framebox (picture)"
@Next "\line"
@Prev "\frame"
@Toc "picture"

\framebox
.........

   @{b}\framebox(width,height)[position]{...}@{ub}

   The @{b}\framebox@{ub} command is exactly the same as the @{b}\makebox@{ub} command,
except that it puts a frame around the outside of the box that it
creates.

   The @{b}framebox@{ub} command produces a rule of thickness @{b}\fboxrule@{ub}, and
leaves a space @{b}\fboxsep@{ub} between the rule and the contents of the box.


@EndNode

@Node "\line" "latex.guide/\line"
@Next "\linethickness"
@Prev "\framebox (picture)"
@Toc "picture"

\line
.....

   @{b}\line(x slope,y slope){length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\line@{ub} command draws a line of the specified @{b}length@{ub} and @{b}slope@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\linethickness" "latex.guide/\linethickness"
@Next "\makebox (picture)"
@Prev "\line"
@Toc "picture"

\linethickness
..............

   @{b}\linethickness{dimension}@{ub}

   Declares the thickness of horizontal and vertical lines in a picture
environment to be @{b}dimension@{ub}, which must be a positive length. It does
not affect the thickness of slanted lines and circles, or the quarter
circles drawn by @{b}\oval@{ub} to form the corners of an oval.


@EndNode

@Node "\makebox (picture)" "latex.guide/\makebox (picture)"
@Next "\multiput"
@Prev "\linethickness"
@Toc "picture"

\makebox
........

   @{b}\makebox(width,height)[position]{...}@{ub}

   The @{b}\makebox@{ub} command for the picture environment is similar to the
normal @{b}\makebox@{ub} command except that you must specify a @{b}width@{ub} and @{b}height@{ub}
in multiples of @{b}\unitlength@{ub}.

   The optional argument, @{b}[position]@{ub}, specifies the quadrant that your
text appears in.  You may select up to two of the following:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}t@{ub} - Moves the item to the top of the rectangle

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}b@{ub} - Moves the item to the bottom

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - Moves the item to the left

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - Moves the item to the right

   See @{"\makebox" Link "\makebox"}.


@EndNode

@Node "\multiput" "latex.guide/\multiput"
@Next "\oval"
@Prev "\makebox (picture)"
@Toc "picture"

\multiput
.........

   @{b}\multiput(x coord,y coord)(delta x,delta y){number of copies}{object}@{ub}

   The @{b}\multiput@{ub} command can be used when you are putting the same
object in a regular pattern across a picture.


@EndNode

@Node "\oval" "latex.guide/\oval"
@Next "\put"
@Prev "\multiput"
@Toc "picture"

\oval
.....

   @{b}\oval(width,height)[portion]@{ub}

   The @{b}\oval@{ub} command produces a rectangle with rounded corners.  The
optional argument, @{b}[portion]@{ub}, allows you to select part of the oval.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}t@{ub} - Selects the top portion

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}b@{ub} - Selects the bottom portion

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - Selects the right portion

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - Selects the left portion


@EndNode

@Node "\put" "latex.guide/\put"
@Next "\shortstack"
@Prev "\oval"
@Toc "picture"

\put
....

   @{b}\put(x coord,y coord){ ...  }@{ub}

   The @{b}\put@{ub} command places the item specified by the mandatory argument
at the given coordinates.


@EndNode

@Node "\shortstack" "latex.guide/\shortstack"
@Next "\vector"
@Prev "\put"
@Toc "picture"

\shortstack
...........

   @{b}\shortstack[position]{...  \\ ...  \\ ...}@{ub}

   The @{b}\shortstack@{ub} command produces a stack of objects.  The valid
positions are:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - Moves the objects to the right of the stack

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - Moves the objects to the left of the stack

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}c@{ub} - Moves the objects to the center of the stack (default)


@EndNode

@Node "\vector" "latex.guide/\vector"
@Next "quotation"
@Prev "\shortstack"
@Toc "picture"

\vector
.......

   @{b}\vector(x slope,y slope){length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\vector@{ub} command draws a line with an arrow of the specified
length and slope.  The @{b}x@{ub} and @{b}y@{ub} values must lie between -4 and +4,
inclusive.


@EndNode

@Node "quotation" "latex.guide/quotation"
@Next "quote"
@Prev "\vector"
@Toc "Environments"

quotation
---------

      \begin{quotation}
       text
      \end{quotation}

   The margins of the @{b}quotation@{ub} environment are indented on the left
and the right.  The text is justified at both margins and there is
paragraph indentation.  Leaving a blank line between text produces a new
paragraph.


@EndNode

@Node "quote" "latex.guide/quote"
@Next "tabbing"
@Prev "quotation"
@Toc "Environments"

quote
-----

      \begin{quote}
       text
      \end{quote}

   The margins of the @{b}quote@{ub} environment are indented on the left and
the right.  The text is justified at both margins.  Leaving a blank line
between text produces a new paragraph.


@EndNode

@Node "tabbing" "latex.guide/tabbing"
@Next "\="
@Prev "quote"
@Toc "Environments"

tabbing
-------

      \begin{tabbing}
      text \= more text \= still more text \= last text \\
      second row \>  \> more \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{tabbing}

   The @{b}tabbing@{ub} environment provides a way to align text in columns.  It
works by setting tab stops and tabbing to them much the way you do with
an ordinary typewriter.


 @{" \= " Link "\="} 
 @{" \> " Link "\>"} 
 @{" \< " Link "\<"} 
 @{" \+ " Link "\+"} 
 @{" \- (tabbing) " Link "\- (tabbing)"} 
 @{" \A " Link "\A"} 
 @{" \` " Link "\`"} 
 @{" \kill " Link "\kill"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\=" "latex.guide/\="
@Next "\>"
@Prev "tabbing"
@Toc "tabbing"

\=
..

   The @{b}\=@{ub} command sets the tab stops.


@EndNode

@Node "\>" "latex.guide/\>"
@Next "\<"
@Prev "\="
@Toc "tabbing"

\>
..

   The @{b}\>@{ub} command causes LaTeX to advance to the next tab stop.


@EndNode

@Node "\<" "latex.guide/\<"
@Next "\+"
@Prev "\>"
@Toc "tabbing"

\<
..

   The @{b}\<@{ub} command allows you to put something to the left of the local
margin without changing the margin.


@EndNode

@Node "\+" "latex.guide/\+"
@Next "\- (tabbing)"
@Prev "\<"
@Toc "tabbing"

\+
..

   The @{b}\+@{ub} command moves the left margin of the next and all the
following commands one tab stop to the right.


@EndNode

@Node "\- (tabbing)" "latex.guide/\- (tabbing)"
@Next "\A"
@Prev "\+"
@Toc "tabbing"

\-
..

   The @{b}\-@{ub} command moves the left margin of the next and all the
following commands one tab stop to the left.


@EndNode

@Node "\A" "latex.guide/\A"
@Next "\`"
@Prev "\- (tabbing)"
@Toc "tabbing"

\'
..

   The @{b}\'@{ub} command moves everything that you have typed so far in the
current column, everything starting from the most recent @{b}\>@{ub}, @{b}\<@{ub}, @{b}\'@{ub}, @{b}\\
@{ub}, or @{b}\kill@{ub} command, to the right of the previous column, flush against
the current column's tab stop.


@EndNode

@Node "\`" "latex.guide/\`"
@Next "\kill"
@Prev "\A"
@Toc "tabbing"

\`
..

   The @{b}\`@{ub} command allows you to put text flushed right against any tab
stop, including tab stop 0.  However, it can't move text to the right
of the last column because there's no tab stop there.  The @{b}\`@{ub} command
moves all the text that follows it, up to the @{b}\\ @{ub} or @{b}\end{tabbing}@{ub}
command that ends the line, to the right margin of the tabbing
environment.  There must be no @{b}\>@{ub} or @{b}\'@{ub} command between the @{b}\`@{ub} and the
command that ends the line.


@EndNode

@Node "\kill" "latex.guide/\kill"
@Next "table"
@Prev "\`"
@Toc "tabbing"

\kill
.....

   The @{b}\kill@{ub} command allows you to set tab stops without producing
text.  It works just like the @{b}\\ @{ub} except that it throws away the
current line instead of producing output for it.  The effect of any @{b}\=@{ub},
@{b}\+@{ub} or @{b}\-@{ub} commands in that line remain in effect.


@EndNode

@Node "table" "latex.guide/table"
@Next "tabular"
@Prev "\kill"
@Toc "Environments"

table
-----

      \begin{table}[placement]
     
       body of the table
     
      \caption{table title}
      \end{table}

   Tables  are objects  that  are not part  of the normal  text,  and
are usually  "floated"  to a convenient  place,  like  the top  of a
page.  Tables will not be split between two pages.

   The optional argument @{b}[placement]@{ub} determines where LaTeX will try to
place your table.  There are four places where LaTeX can possibly put a
float:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}h@{ub} : Here - at the position in the text where the table
     environment appears.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}t@{ub} : Top - at the top of a text page.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}b@{ub} : Bottom - at the bottom of a text page.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}p@{ub} : Page of floats - on a separate float page, which is a page
     containing no text, only floats.

   The standard @{b}report@{ub} and @{b}article@{ub} styles use the default placement
@{b}[tbp]@{ub}.

   The body of the table is made up of whatever text, LaTeX commands,
etc., you wish.  The @{b}\caption@{ub} command allows you to title your table.


@EndNode

@Node "tabular" "latex.guide/tabular"
@Next "\cline"
@Prev "table"
@Toc "Environments"

tabular
-------

      \begin{tabular}[pos]{cols}
      column 1 entry & column 2 entry ... & column n entry \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{tabular}
     
                     or
     
      \begin{tabular*}{width}[pos]{cols}
      column 1 entry & column 2 entry ... & column n entry \\
      .
      .
      .
      \end{tabular*}

   These environments produce a box consisting of a sequence of rows of
items, aligned vertically in columns.  The mandatory and optional
arguments consist of:

@{b}width@{ub}
     Specifies the width of the @{b}tabular*@{ub} environment.  There must be
     rubber space between columns that can stretch to fill out the
     specified width.

@{b}pos@{ub}
     Specifies the vertical position; default is alignment on the
     center of the environment.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}t@{ub} - align on top row

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}b@{ub} - align on bottom row

@{b}cols@{ub}
     Specifies the column formatting.  It consists of a sequence of the
     following specifiers, corresponding to the sequence of columns and
     intercolumn material.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - A column of left-aligned items.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - A column of right-aligned items.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}c@{ub} - A column of centred items.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}|@{ub} - A vertical line the full height and depth of the
          environment.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b} @{text}@{ub} - This inserts text in every row.  An
          @-expression suppresses the intercolumn space normally
          inserted between columns; any desired space between the
          inserted text and the adjacent items must be included in
          text.  An @{b}\extracolsep{wd}@{ub} command in an @-expression causes
          an extra space of width @{b}wd@{ub} to appear to the left of all
          subsequent columns, until countermanded by another
          @{b}\extracolsep@{ub} command.  Unlike ordinary intercolumn space, this
          extra space is not suppressed by an @-expression.  An
          @{b}\extracolsep@{ub} command can be used only in an @-expression in
          the @{b}cols@{ub} argument.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b} p{wd}@{ub} - Produces a column with each item typeset in a
          parbox of width @{b}wd@{ub}, as if it were the argument of a
          @{b}\parbox[t]{wd}@{ub} command.  However, a @{b}\\ @{ub} may not appear in the
          item, except in the following situations:
            1. inside an environment like @{b}minipage@{ub}, @{b}array@{ub}, or @{b}tabular@{ub}.

            2. inside an explicit @{b}\parbox@{ub}.

            3. in the scope of a @{b}\centering@{ub}, @{b}\raggedright@{ub}, or
               @{b}\raggedleft@{ub} declaration.  The latter declarations must
               appear inside braces or an environment when used in a
               @{b}p-column@{ub} element.

        @{b}*@{ub}     @{b} *{num}{cols}@{ub} - Equivalent to @{b}num@{ub} copies of @{b}cols@{ub}, where
          @{b}num@{ub} is any positive integer and @{b}cols@{ub} is any list of
          column-specifiers, which may contain another @{b}*-expression@{ub}.


 @{" \cline " Link "\cline"} 
 @{" \hline " Link "\hline"} 
 @{" \multicolumn " Link "\multicolumn"} 
 @{" \vline " Link "\vline"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\cline" "latex.guide/\cline"
@Next "\hline"
@Prev "tabular"
@Toc "tabular"

\cline
......

   @{b}\cline{i-j}@{ub}

   The @{b}\cline@{ub} command draws horizontal lines across the columns
specified, beginning in column @{b}i@{ub} and ending in column @{b}j@{ub}, which are
identified in the mandatory argument.


@EndNode

@Node "\hline" "latex.guide/\hline"
@Next "\multicolumn"
@Prev "\cline"
@Toc "tabular"

\hline
......

   The @{b}\hline@{ub} command will draw a horizontal line the width of the
table.  It's most commonly used to draw a line at the top, bottom, and
between the rows of the table.


@EndNode

@Node "\multicolumn" "latex.guide/\multicolumn"
@Next "\vline"
@Prev "\hline"
@Toc "tabular"

\multicolumn
............

   @{b}\multicolumn{cols}{pos}{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\multicolumn@{ub} is used to make an entry that spans several
columns.  The first mandatory argument, @{b}cols@{ub}, specifies the number of
columns to span.  The second mandatory argument, @{b}pos@{ub}, specifies the
formatting of the entry; @{b}c@{ub} for centred, @{b}l@{ub} for flushleft, @{b}r@{ub} for
flushright.  The third mandatory argument, @{b}text@{ub}, specifies what text is
to make up the entry.


@EndNode

@Node "\vline" "latex.guide/\vline"
@Next "thebibliography"
@Prev "\multicolumn"
@Toc "tabular"

\vline
......

   The @{b}\vline@{ub} command will draw a vertical line extending the full
height and depth of its row.  An @{b}\hfill@{ub} command can be used to move the
line to the edge of the column.  It can also be used in an @-expression.


@EndNode

@Node "thebibliography" "latex.guide/thebibliography"
@Next "\bibitem"
@Prev "\vline"
@Toc "Environments"

thebibliography
---------------

      \begin{thebibliography}{widest-label}
      \bibitem[label]{cite_key}
      .
      .
      .
      \end{thebibliography}

   The @{b}thebibliography@{ub} environment produces a bibliography or reference
list.  In the @{b}article@{ub} style, this reference list is labelled
"References"; in the @{b}report@{ub} style, it is labelled "Bibliography".

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}widest-label@{ub}: Text that, when printed, is approximately as wide
     as the widest item label produces by the @{b}\bibitem@{ub} commands.


 @{" \bibitem " Link "\bibitem"} 
 @{" \cite " Link "\cite"} 
 @{" \nocite " Link "\nocite"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\bibitem" "latex.guide/\bibitem"
@Next "\cite"
@Prev "thebibliography"
@Toc "thebibliography"

\bibitem
........

   @{b}\bibitem[label]{cite_key}@{ub}

   The @{b}\bibitem@{ub} command generates an entry labelled by @{b}label@{ub}.  If the
@{b}label@{ub} argument is missing, a number is generated as the @{b}label@{ub}, using
the @{b}enumi@{ub} counter.  The @{b}cite_key@{ub} is any sequence of letters, numbers,
and punctuation symbols not containing a comma.  This command writes an
entry on the @{b}.aux@{ub} file containing @{b}cite_key@{ub} and the item's @{b}label@{ub}.  When
this @{b}.aux@{ub} file is read by the @{b}\begin{document}@{ub} command, the item's
@{b}label@{ub} is associated with @{b}cite_key@{ub}, causing the reference to
@{b}cite_key@{ub} by a @{b}\cite@{ub} command to produce the associated @{b}label@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\cite" "latex.guide/\cite"
@Next "\nocite"
@Prev "\bibitem"
@Toc "thebibliography"

\cite
.....

   @{b}\cite[text]{key_list}@{ub}

   The @{b}key_list@{ub} argument is a list of citation keys.  This command
generates an in-text citation to the references associated with the keys
in @{b}key_list@{ub} by entries on the @{b}.aux@{ub} file read by the @{b}\begin{document}@{ub}
command.


@EndNode

@Node "\nocite" "latex.guide/\nocite"
@Next "theorem"
@Prev "\cite"
@Toc "thebibliography"

\nocite
.......

   @{b}\nocite{key_list}@{ub}

   The @{b}\nocite@{ub} command produces no text, but writes @{b}key_list@{ub}, which is
a list of one or more citation keys, on the @{b}.aux@{ub} file.


@EndNode

@Node "theorem" "latex.guide/theorem"
@Next "titlepage"
@Prev "\nocite"
@Toc "Environments"

theorem
-------

      \begin{theorem}
       theorem text
      \end{theorem}

   The @{b}theorem@{ub} environment produces "Theorem x" in boldface followed by
your theorem text.


@EndNode

@Node "titlepage" "latex.guide/titlepage"
@Next "verbatim"
@Prev "theorem"
@Toc "Environments"

titlepage
---------

      \begin{titlepage}
       text
      \end{titlepage}

   The @{b}titlepage@{ub} environment creates a title page, i.e.  a page with no
printed page number or heading.  It also causes the following page to be
numbered page one.  Formatting the title page is left to you.  The
@{b}\today@{ub} command comes in handy for title pages.


@EndNode

@Node "verbatim" "latex.guide/verbatim"
@Next "\verb"
@Prev "titlepage"
@Toc "Environments"

verbatim
--------

      \begin{verbatim}
       text
      \end{verbatim}

   The @{b}verbatim@{ub} environment is a paragraph-making environment that gets
LaTeX to print exactly what you type in.  It turns LaTeX into a
typewriter with carriage returns and blanks having the same effect that
they would on a typewriter.


 @{" \verb " Link "\verb"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\verb" "latex.guide/\verb"
@Next "verse"
@Prev "verbatim"
@Toc "verbatim"

\verb
.....

   @{b}\verb char literal_text char \verb*char literal_text char@{ub}

   Typesets @{b}literal_text@{ub} exactly as typed, including special characters
and spaces, using a typewriter (@{b}\tt@{ub}) type style.  There may be no space
between @{b}\verb@{ub} or @{b}\verb*@{ub} and @{b}char@{ub} (space is shown here only for
clarity).  The @{b}*-form@{ub} differs only in that spaces are printed.


@EndNode

@Node "verse" "latex.guide/verse"
@Next "Footnotes"
@Prev "\verb"
@Toc "Environments"

verse
-----

      \begin{verse}
       text
      \end{verse}

   The @{b}verse@{ub} environment is designed for poetry, though you may find
other uses for it.


@EndNode

@Node "Footnotes" "latex.guide/Footnotes"
@Next "\footnote"
@Prev "verse"
@Toc "Commands"

Footnotes
=========

   @{b}Footnotes@{ub} can be produced in one of two ways.  They can be produced
with one command, the @{b}\footnote@{ub} command.  They can also be produced
with two commands, the @{b}\footnotemark@{ub} and the @{b}\footnotetext@{ub} commands.
See the specific command for information on why you would use one over
the other.


 @{" \footnote " Link "\footnote"} 
 @{" \footnotemark " Link "\footnotemark"} 
 @{" \footnotetext " Link "\footnotetext"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\footnote" "latex.guide/\footnote"
@Next "\footnotemark"
@Prev "Footnotes"
@Toc "Footnotes"

\footnote
---------

   @{b}\footnote[number]{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\footnote@{ub} command places the numbered footnote @{b}text@{ub} at the
bottom of the current page.  The optional argument, @{b}number@{ub}, is used to
change the default footnote number.  This command can only be used in
outer paragraph mode.


@EndNode

@Node "\footnotemark" "latex.guide/\footnotemark"
@Next "\footnotetext"
@Prev "\footnote"
@Toc "Footnotes"

\footnotemark
-------------

   The @{b}\footnotemark@{ub} command puts the footnote @{b}number@{ub} in the text.
This command can be used in inner paragraph mode.  The text of the
footnote is supplied by the @{b}\footnotetext@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "\footnotetext" "latex.guide/\footnotetext"
@Next "Lengths"
@Prev "\footnotemark"
@Toc "Footnotes"

\footnotetext
-------------

   @{b}\footnotetext[number]{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\footnotetext@{ub} command produces the @{b}text@{ub} to be placed at the
bottom of the page.  This command can come anywhere after the
@{b}\footnotemark@{ub} command.  The @{b}\footnotetext@{ub} command must appear in outer
paragraph mode.

   The optional argument, @{b}number@{ub}, is used to change the default
footnote number.


@EndNode

@Node "Lengths" "latex.guide/Lengths"
@Next "\newlength"
@Prev "\footnotetext"
@Toc "Commands"

Lengths
=======

   A @{b}length@{ub} is a measure of distance.  Many LaTeX commands take a
length as an argument.


 @{" \newlength " Link "\newlength"} 
 @{" \setlength " Link "\setlength"} 
 @{" \addtolength " Link "\addtolength"} 
 @{" \settowidth " Link "\settowidth"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\newlength" "latex.guide/\newlength"
@Next "\setlength"
@Prev "Lengths"
@Toc "Lengths"

\newlength
----------

   @{b}\newlength{\gnat}@{ub}

   The @{b}\newlength@{ub} command defines the mandatory argument, @{b}\gnat@{ub}, as a
@{b}length@{ub} command with a value of @{b}0in@{ub}.  An error occurs if a @{b}\gnat@{ub} command
already exists.


@EndNode

@Node "\setlength" "latex.guide/\setlength"
@Next "\addtolength"
@Prev "\newlength"
@Toc "Lengths"

\setlength
----------

   @{b}\setlength{\gnat}{length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\setlength@{ub} command is used to set the value of a @{b}length@{ub} command.
The @{b}length@{ub} argument can be expressed in any terms of length LaTeX
understands, i.e., inches (@{b}in@{ub}), millimeters (@{b}mm@{ub}), points (@{b}pt@{ub}), etc.


@EndNode

@Node "\addtolength" "latex.guide/\addtolength"
@Next "\settowidth"
@Prev "\setlength"
@Toc "Lengths"

\addtolength
------------

   @{b}\addtolength{\gnat}{length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\addtolength@{ub} command increments a "length command" by the amount
specified in the @{b}length@{ub} argument.  It can be a negative amount.


@EndNode

@Node "\settowidth" "latex.guide/\settowidth"
@Next "Letters"
@Prev "\addtolength"
@Toc "Lengths"

\settowidth
-----------

   @{b}\settowidth{\gnat}{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\settowidth@{ub} command sets the value of a @{b}length@{ub} command equal to
the width of the @{b}text@{ub} argument.


@EndNode

@Node "Letters" "latex.guide/Letters"
@Next "\opening"
@Prev "\settowidth"
@Toc "Commands"

Letters
=======

   You can use LaTeX to typeset letters, both personal and business.
The @{b}letter@{ub} document style is designed to make a number of letters at
once, although you can make just one if you so desire.

   Your @{b}.tex@{ub} source file has the same minimum commands as the other
document styles, i.e., you must have the following commands as a
minimum:
      \documentstyle{letter}
      \begin{document}
       ... letters ...
      \end{document}

   Each letter is a @{b}letter@{ub} environment, whose argument is the name and
address of the recipient.  For example, you might have:
      \begin{letter}{Mr. Joe Smith\\ 2345 Princess St.
           \\ Edinburgh, EH1 1AA}
        ...
      \end{letter}

   The letter itself begins with the @{b}\opening@{ub} command.  The text of the
letter follows.  It is typed as ordinary LaTeX input.  Commands that
make no sense in a letter, like @{b}\chapter@{ub}, don't work.  The letter
closes with a @{b}\closing@{ub} command.

   After the @{b}closing@{ub}, you can have additional material.  The @{b}\cc@{ub}
command produces the usual "cc: ...".  There's also a similar @{b}\encl@{ub}
command for a list of enclosures.


 @{" \opening " Link "\opening"} 
 @{" \closing " Link "\closing"} 
 @{" Declarations " Link "Declarations"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\opening" "latex.guide/\opening"
@Next "\closing"
@Prev "Letters"
@Toc "Letters"

\opening
--------

   @{b}\opening{text}@{ub}

   The letter begins with the @{b}\opening@{ub} command.  The mandatory
argument, @{b}text@{ub}, is whatever text you wish to start your letter, i.e.,
      \opening{Dear Joe,}


@EndNode

@Node "\closing" "latex.guide/\closing"
@Next "Declarations"
@Prev "\opening"
@Toc "Letters"

\closing
--------

   @{b}\closing{text}@{ub}

   The letter closes with a @{b}\closing@{ub} command, i.e.,
      \closing{Best Regards,}


@EndNode

@Node "Declarations" "latex.guide/Declarations"
@Next "\address"
@Prev "\closing"
@Toc "Letters"

Declarations
------------

   The following commands are declarations which take a single argument.


 @{" \address " Link "\address"} 
 @{" \signature " Link "\signature"} 
 @{" \location " Link "\location"} 
 @{" \telephone " Link "\telephone"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\address" "latex.guide/\address"
@Next "\signature"
@Prev "Declarations"
@Toc "Declarations"

\address
--------

   @{b}\address{Return address}@{ub}

   The return address, as it should appear on the letter and the
envelope.  Separate lines of the address should be separated by @{b}\\ @{ub}
commands.  If you do not make an @{b}\address@{ub} declaration, then the letter
will be formatted for copying onto your organisation's standard
letterhead.  (See @{"Overview" Link "Overview"}, for details on your local implementation).
If you give an @{b}\address@{ub} declaration, then the letter will be formatted
as a personal letter.


@EndNode

@Node "\signature" "latex.guide/\signature"
@Next "\location"
@Prev "\address"
@Toc "Declarations"

\signature
----------

   @{b}\signature{Your name}@{ub}

   Your name, as it should appear at the end of the letter underneath
the space for your signature.  Items that should go on separate lines
should be separated by @{b}\\ @{ub} commands.


@EndNode

@Node "\location" "latex.guide/\location"
@Next "\telephone"
@Prev "\signature"
@Toc "Declarations"

\location
---------

   @{b}\location{address}@{ub}

   This modifies your organisation's standard address.  This only
appears if the @{b}firstpage@{ub} pagestyle is selected.


@EndNode

@Node "\telephone" "latex.guide/\telephone"
@Next "Line & Page Breaking"
@Prev "\location"
@Toc "Declarations"

\telephone
----------

   @{b}\telephone{number}@{ub}

   This is your telephone number.  This only appears if the @{b}firstpage@{ub}
pagestyle is selected.


@EndNode

@Node "Line & Page Breaking" "latex.guide/Line & Page Breaking"
@Next "\\"
@Prev "\telephone"
@Toc "Commands"

Line & Page Breaking
====================

   The first thing LaTeX does when processing ordinary text is to
translate your input file into a string of glyphs and spaces.  To
produce a printed document, this string must be broken into lines, and
these lines must be broken into pages.  In some environments, you do
the line breaking yourself with the @{b}\\ @{ub} command, but LaTeX usually does
it for you.


 @{" \\ " Link "\\"} 
 @{" \- (hyphenation) " Link "\- (hyphenation)"} 
 @{" \cleardoublepage " Link "\cleardoublepage"} 
 @{" \clearpage " Link "\clearpage"} 
 @{" \hyphenation " Link "\hyphenation"} 
 @{" \linebreak " Link "\linebreak"} 
 @{" \newline " Link "\newline"} 
 @{" \newpage " Link "\newpage"} 
 @{" \nolinebreak " Link "\nolinebreak"} 
 @{" \nopagebreak " Link "\nopagebreak"} 
 @{" \pagebreak " Link "\pagebreak"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\\" "latex.guide/\\"
@Next "\- (hyphenation)"
@Prev "Line & Page Breaking"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\\
--

   @{b}\\[*][extra-space]@{ub}

   The @{b}\\ @{ub} command tells LaTeX to start a new line.  It has an optional
argument, @{b}extra-space@{ub}, that specifies how much extra vertical space is
to be inserted before the next line.  This can be a negative amount.

   The @{b}\\*@{ub} command is the same as the ordinary @{b}\\ @{ub} command except that
it tells LaTeX not to start a new page after the line.


@EndNode

@Node "\- (hyphenation)" "latex.guide/\- (hyphenation)"
@Next "\cleardoublepage"
@Prev "\\"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\-
--

   The @{b}\-@{ub} command tells LaTeX that it may hyphenate the word at that
point.  LaTeX is very good at hyphenating, and it will usually find all
correct hyphenation points.  The @{b}\-@{ub} command is used for the exceptional
cases.


@EndNode

@Node "\cleardoublepage" "latex.guide/\cleardoublepage"
@Next "\clearpage"
@Prev "\- (hyphenation)"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\cleardoublepage
----------------

   The @{b}\cleardoublepage@{ub} command ends the current page and causes all
figures and tables that have so far appeared in the input to be printed.
In a two-sided printing style, it also makes the next page a right-hand
(odd-numbered) page, producing a blank page if necessary.


@EndNode

@Node "\clearpage" "latex.guide/\clearpage"
@Next "\hyphenation"
@Prev "\cleardoublepage"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\clearpage
----------

   The @{b}\clearpage@{ub} command ends the current page and causes all figures
and tables that have so far appeared in the input to be printed.


@EndNode

@Node "\hyphenation" "latex.guide/\hyphenation"
@Next "\linebreak"
@Prev "\clearpage"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\hyphenation
------------

   @{b}\hyphenation{words}@{ub}

   The @{b}\hyphenation@{ub} command declares allowed hyphenation points, where
@{b}words@{ub} is a list of words, separated by spaces, in which each
hyphenation point is indicated by a @{b}-@{ub} character.


@EndNode

@Node "\linebreak" "latex.guide/\linebreak"
@Next "\newline"
@Prev "\hyphenation"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\linebreak
----------

   @{b}\linebreak[number]@{ub}

   The @{b}\linebreak@{ub} command tells LaTeX to break the current line at the
point of the command.  With the optional argument, @{b}number@{ub}, you can
convert the @{b}\linebreak@{ub} command from a demand to a request.  The number
must be a number from 0 to 4.  The higher the number, the more
insistent the request is.

   The @{b}\linebreak@{ub} command causes LaTeX to stretch the line so it
extends to the right margin.


@EndNode

@Node "\newline" "latex.guide/\newline"
@Next "\newpage"
@Prev "\linebreak"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\newline
--------

   The @{b}\newline@{ub} command breaks the line right where it is.  The
@{b}\newline@{ub} command can be used only in paragraph mode.


@EndNode

@Node "\newpage" "latex.guide/\newpage"
@Next "\nolinebreak"
@Prev "\newline"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\newpage
--------

   The @{b}\newpage@{ub} command ends the current page.


@EndNode

@Node "\nolinebreak" "latex.guide/\nolinebreak"
@Next "\nopagebreak"
@Prev "\newpage"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\nolinebreak
------------

   @{b}\nolinebreak[number]@{ub}

   The @{b}\nolinebreak@{ub} command prevents LaTeX from breaking the current
line at the point of the command.  With the optional argument, @{b}number@{ub},
you can convert the @{b}\nolinebreak@{ub} command from a demand to a request.
The number must be a number from 0 to 4.  The higher the number, the
more insistent the request is.


@EndNode

@Node "\nopagebreak" "latex.guide/\nopagebreak"
@Next "\pagebreak"
@Prev "\nolinebreak"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\nopagebreak
------------

   @{b}\nopagebreak[number]@{ub}

   The @{b}\nopagebreak@{ub} command prevents LaTeX from breaking the current
page at the point of the command.  With the optional argument, @{b}number@{ub},
you can convert the @{b}\nopagebreak@{ub} command from a demand to a request.
The number must be a number from 0 to 4.  The higher the number, the
more insistent the request is.


@EndNode

@Node "\pagebreak" "latex.guide/\pagebreak"
@Next "Making Paragraphs"
@Prev "\nopagebreak"
@Toc "Line & Page Breaking"

\pagebreak
----------

   @{b}\pagebreak[number]@{ub}

   The @{b}\pagebreak@{ub} command tells LaTeX to break the current page at the
point of the command.  With the optional argument, @{b}number@{ub}, you can
convert the @{b}\pagebreak@{ub} command from a demand to a request.  The number
must be a number from 0 to 4.  The higher the number, the more
insistent the request is.


@EndNode

@Node "Making Paragraphs" "latex.guide/Making Paragraphs"
@Next "\indent"
@Prev "\pagebreak"
@Toc "Commands"

Making Paragraphs
=================

   A paragraph is ended by one or more completely blank lines - lines
not containing even an @{b}%@{ub}.  A blank line should not appear where a new
paragraph cannot be started, such as in math mode or in the argument of
a sectioning command.


 @{" \indent " Link "\indent"} 
 @{" \noindent " Link "\noindent"} 
 @{" \par " Link "\par"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\indent" "latex.guide/\indent"
@Next "\noindent"
@Prev "Making Paragraphs"
@Toc "Making Paragraphs"

\indent
-------

   @{b}\indent@{ub}

   This produces a horizontal space whose width equals the width of the
paragraph indentation.  It is used to add paragraph indentation where it
would otherwise be suppressed.


@EndNode

@Node "\noindent" "latex.guide/\noindent"
@Next "\par"
@Prev "\indent"
@Toc "Making Paragraphs"

\noindent
---------

   @{b}\noindent@{ub}

   When used at the beginning of the paragraph, it suppresses the
paragraph indentation.  It has no effect when used in the middle of a
paragraph.


@EndNode

@Node "\par" "latex.guide/\par"
@Next "Math Formulae"
@Prev "\noindent"
@Toc "Making Paragraphs"

\par
----

   Equivalent to a blank line; often used to make command or environment
definitions easier to read.


@EndNode

@Node "Math Formulae" "latex.guide/Math Formulae"
@Next "Subscripts & Superscripts"
@Prev "\par"
@Toc "Commands"

Math Formulae
=============

   There are three environments that put LaTeX in math mode:
@{b}math@{ub}
     For Formulae that appear right in the text.

@{b}displaymath@{ub}
     For Formulae that appear on their own line.

@{b}equation@{ub}
     The same as the displaymath environment except that it adds an
     equation number in the right margin.

   The @{b}math@{ub} environment can be used in both paragraph and LR mode, but
the @{b}displaymath@{ub} and @{b}equation@{ub} environments can be used only in paragraph
mode.  The @{b}math@{ub} and @{b}displaymath@{ub} environments are used so often that
they have the following short forms:
         \(...\)     instead of     \begin{math}...\end{math}
     
         \[...\]     instead of     \begin{displaymath}...\end{displaymath}

   In fact, the @{b}math@{ub} environment is so common that it has an even
shorter form:
         $ ... $     instead of     \(...\)


 @{" Subscripts & Superscripts " Link "Subscripts & Superscripts"} 
 @{" Math Symbols " Link "Math Symbols"} 
 @{" Spacing in Math Mode " Link "Spacing in Math Mode"} 
 @{" Math Miscellany " Link "Math Miscellany"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Subscripts & Superscripts" "latex.guide/Subscripts & Superscripts"
@Next "Math Symbols"
@Prev "Math Formulae"
@Toc "Math Formulae"

Subscripts & Superscripts
-------------------------

   To get an expression @{b}exp@{ub} to appear as a subscript, you just type @{b}
_{exp}@{ub}.  To get @{b}exp@{ub} to appear as a superscript, you type @{b} ^{exp}@{ub}. LaTeX
handles superscripted superscripts and all of that stuff in the natural
way.  It even does the right thing when something has both a subscript
and a superscript.


@EndNode

@Node "Math Symbols" "latex.guide/Math Symbols"
@Next "Spacing in Math Mode"
@Prev "Subscripts & Superscripts"
@Toc "Math Formulae"

Math Symbols
------------

   LaTeX provides almost any mathematical symbol you're likely to need.
The commands for generating them can be used only in math mode.  For
example, if you include @{b}$\pi$@{ub} in your source, you will get the symbol
"pi" in your output.


@EndNode

@Node "Spacing in Math Mode" "latex.guide/Spacing in Math Mode"
@Next "Math Miscellany"
@Prev "Math Symbols"
@Toc "Math Formulae"

Spacing in Math Mode
--------------------

   In a @{b}math@{ub} environment, LaTeX ignores the spaces you type and puts in
the spacing that it thinks is best.  LaTeX formats mathematics the way
it's done in mathematics texts.  If you want different spacing, LaTeX
provides the following four commands for use in math mode:
  1.     @{b}\;@{ub} - a thick space

  2.     @{b}\:@{ub} - a medium space

  3.     @{b}\,@{ub} - a thin space

  4.     @{b}\!@{ub} - a negative thin space


@EndNode

@Node "Math Miscellany" "latex.guide/Math Miscellany"
@Next "Modes"
@Prev "Spacing in Math Mode"
@Toc "Math Formulae"

Math Miscellany
---------------

@{b}\cdots@{ub}
     The @{b}\cdots@{ub} command produces a horizontal ellipsis where the dots
     are raised to the center of the line.

@{b}\ddots@{ub}
     The @{b}\ddots@{ub} command produces a diagonal ellipsis.

@{b}\frac@{ub}
     @{b}\frac{num}{den}@{ub} The @{b}\frac@{ub} command produces the fraction @{b}num@{ub}
     divided by @{b}den@{ub}.

@{b}\ldots@{ub}
     The @{b}\ldots@{ub} command produces an ellipsis.  This command works in
     any mode, not just math mode.

@{b}\overbrace@{ub}
     @{b}\overbrace{text}@{ub} The @{b}\overbrace@{ub} command generates a brace over
     text.

@{b}\overline@{ub}
     @{b}\overline{text}@{ub} The @{b}\overline@{ub} command causes the argument text to
     be overlined.

@{b}\sqrt@{ub}
     @{b}\sqrt[root]{arg}@{ub} The @{b}\sqrt@{ub} command produces the square root of its
     argument.  The optional argument, @{b}root@{ub}, determines what root to
     produce, i.e., the cube root of @{b}x+y@{ub} would be typed as
     @{b}$\sqrt[3]{x+y}$@{ub}.

@{b}\underbrace@{ub}
     @{b}\underbrace{text}@{ub} The @{b}\underbrace@{ub} command generates text with a
     brace underneath.

@{b}\underline@{ub}
     @{b}\underline{text}@{ub} The @{b}\underline@{ub} command causes the argument text
     to be underlined.  This command can also be used in paragraph and
     LR modes.

@{b}\vdots@{ub}
     The @{b}\vdots@{ub} command produces a vertical ellipsis.


@EndNode

@Node "Modes" "latex.guide/Modes"
@Next "Page Styles"
@Prev "Math Miscellany"
@Toc "Commands"

Modes
=====

   When LaTeX is processing your input text, it is always in one of
three modes:

   @{b}*@{ub} Paragraph mode

   @{b}*@{ub} Math mode

   @{b}*@{ub} Left-to-right mode, called LR mode for short

   LaTeX changes mode only when it goes up or down a staircase to a
different level, though not all level changes produce mode changes.
Mode changes occur only when entering or leaving an environment, or when
LaTeX is processing the argument of certain text-producing commands.

   "Paragraph mode" is the most common; it's the one LaTeX is in when
processing ordinary text.  In that mode, LaTeX breaks your text into
lines and breaks the lines into pages.  LaTeX is in "math mode" when
it's generating a mathematical formula.  In "LR mode", as in paragraph
mode, LaTeX considers the output that it produces to be a string of
words with spaces between them.  However, unlike paragraph mode, LaTeX
keeps going from left to right; it never starts a new line in LR mode.
Even if you put a hundred words into an @{b}\mbox@{ub}, LaTeX would keep
typesetting them from left to right inside a single box, and then
complain because the resulting box was too wide to fit on the line.

   LaTeX is in LR mode when it starts making a box with an @{b}\mbox@{ub}
command.  You can get it to enter a different mode inside the box - for
example, you can make it enter math mode to put a formula in the box.
There are also several text-producing commands and environments for
making a box that put LaTeX in paragraph mode.  The box make by one of
these commands or environments will be called a @{b}parbox@{ub}.  When LaTeX is
in paragraph mode while making a box, it is said to be in "inner
paragraph mode".  Its normal paragraph mode, which it starts out in, is
called "outer paragraph mode".


@EndNode

@Node "Page Styles" "latex.guide/Page Styles"
@Next "\maketitle"
@Prev "Modes"
@Toc "Commands"

Page Styles
===========

   The @{b}\documentstyle@{ub} command determines the size and position of the
page's head and foot.  The page style determines what goes in them.


 @{" \maketitle " Link "\maketitle"} 
 @{" \pagenumbering " Link "\pagenumbering"} 
 @{" \pagestyle " Link "\pagestyle"} 
 @{" \thispagestyle " Link "\thispagestyle"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\maketitle" "latex.guide/\maketitle"
@Next "\author"
@Prev "Page Styles"
@Toc "Page Styles"

\maketitle
----------

   @{b}\maketitle@{ub}

   The @{b}\maketitle@{ub} command generates a title on a separate title page -
except in the @{b}article@{ub} style, where the title normally goes at the top
of the first page.  Information used to produce the title is obtained
from the following declarations:

   See @{"Page Styles" Link "Page Styles"} for the commands to give the information.


 @{" \author " Link "\author"} 
 @{" \date " Link "\date"} 
 @{" \thanks " Link "\thanks"} 
 @{" \title " Link "\title"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\author" "latex.guide/\author"
@Next "\date"
@Prev "\maketitle"
@Toc "\maketitle"

\author
-------

   @{b}\author{names}@{ub}

   The @{b}\author@{ub} command declares the author(s), where @{b}names@{ub} is a list of
authors separated by @{b}\and@{ub} commands.  Use @{b}\\ @{ub} to separate lines within a
single author's entry - for example, to give the author's institution
or address.

   NOTE: The @{b}milstd@{ub} and @{b}book-form@{ub} styles have re-defined the @{b}\maketitle@{ub}
command.  The @{b}\title@{ub} declaration is the only command of those shown
below that has any meaning.


@EndNode

@Node "\date" "latex.guide/\date"
@Next "\thanks"
@Prev "\author"
@Toc "\maketitle"

\date
-----

   @{b}\date{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\date@{ub} command declares text to be the document's date.  With no
@{b}\date@{ub} command, the current date is used.


@EndNode

@Node "\thanks" "latex.guide/\thanks"
@Next "\title"
@Prev "\date"
@Toc "\maketitle"

\thanks
-------

   @{b}\thanks{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\thanks@{ub} command produces a @{b}footnote@{ub} to the title.


@EndNode

@Node "\title" "latex.guide/\title"
@Next "\pagenumbering"
@Prev "\thanks"
@Toc "\maketitle"

\title
------

   @{b}\title{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\title@{ub} command declares @{b}text@{ub} to be the title.  Use @{b}\\ @{ub} to tell
LaTeX where to start a new line in a long title.


@EndNode

@Node "\pagenumbering" "latex.guide/\pagenumbering"
@Next "\pagestyle"
@Prev "\title"
@Toc "Page Styles"

\pagenumbering
--------------

   @{b}\pagenumbering{num_style}@{ub}

   Specifies the style of page numbers.  Possible values of @{b}num_style@{ub}
are:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}arabic@{ub} - Arabic numerals

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}roman@{ub} - Lowercase roman numerals

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Roman@{ub} - Uppercase roman numerals

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}alph@{ub} - Lowercase letters

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Alph@{ub} - Uppercase letters


@EndNode

@Node "\pagestyle" "latex.guide/\pagestyle"
@Next "\mark"
@Prev "\pagenumbering"
@Toc "Page Styles"

\pagestyle
----------

   @{b}\pagestyle{option}@{ub}

   The @{b}\pagestyle@{ub} command changes the style from the current page on
throughout the remainder of your document.

   The valid options are:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}plain@{ub} - Just a plain page number.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}empty@{ub} - Produces empty heads and feet - no page numbers.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}headings@{ub} - Puts running headings on each page.  The document
     style specifies what goes in the headings.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}myheadings@{ub} - You specify what is to go in the heading with the
     @{b}\markboth@{ub} or the @{b}\markright@{ub} commands.


 @{" \mark " Link "\mark"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\mark" "latex.guide/\mark"
@Next "\thispagestyle"
@Prev "\pagestyle"
@Toc "\pagestyle"

\mark
-----

     \markboth{left head}{right head}
     \markright{right head}

   The @{b}\markboth@{ub} and @{b}\markright@{ub} commands are used in conjunction with
the page style @{b}myheadings@{ub} for setting either both or just the right
heading.  In addition to their use with the @{b}myheadings@{ub} page style, you
can use them to override the normal headings in the @{b}headings@{ub} style,
since LaTeX uses these same commands to generate those heads.  You
should note that a "left-hand heading" is generated by the last
@{b}\markboth@{ub} command before the end of the page, while a "right-hand
heading" is generated by the first @{b}\markboth@{ub} or @{b}\markright@{ub} that comes
on the page if there is one, otherwise by the last one before the page.


@EndNode

@Node "\thispagestyle" "latex.guide/\thispagestyle"
@Next "Sectioning"
@Prev "\mark"
@Toc "Page Styles"

\thispagestyle
--------------

   @{b}\thispagestyle{option}@{ub}

   The @{b}\thispagestyle@{ub} command works in the same manner as the
@{b}\pagestyle@{ub} command except that it changes the style for the current
page only.


@EndNode

@Node "Sectioning" "latex.guide/Sectioning"
@Next "\appendix"
@Prev "\thispagestyle"
@Toc "Commands"

Sectioning
==========

   Sectioning commands provide the means to structure your text into
units.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\part@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\chapter@{ub} (report style only)

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\section@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\subsection@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\subsubsection@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\paragraph@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\subparagraph@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\subsubparagraph@{ub} (milstd and book-form styles only)

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}\subsubsubparagraph@{ub} (milstd and book-form styles only)

   All sectioning commands take the same general form, i.e.,

   @{b}\chapter[optional]{title}@{ub}

   In addition to providing the heading in the text, the mandatory
argument of the sectioning command can appear in two other places:

  1. The table of contents

  2. The running head at the top of the page

   You may not want the same thing to appear in these other two places
as appears in the text heading.  To handle this situation, the
sectioning commands have an @{b}optional@{ub} argument that provides the text for
these other two purposes.

   The "sectioning commands" have @{b}*-forms@{ub} that print a @{b}title@{ub}, but do
not include a number and do not make an entry in the table of contents.
For example, the @{b}*-form@{ub} of the @{b}\subsection@{ub} command could look like:

   @{b}\subsection*{Example subsection}@{ub}


 @{" \appendix " Link "\appendix"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\appendix" "latex.guide/\appendix"
@Next "Spaces & Boxes"
@Prev "Sectioning"
@Toc "Sectioning"

\appendix
---------

   @{b}\appendix@{ub}

   The @{b}\appendix@{ub} command changes the way sectional units are numbered.
The @{b}\appendix@{ub} command generates no text and does not affect the
numbering or parts.


@EndNode

@Node "Spaces & Boxes" "latex.guide/Spaces & Boxes"
@Next "\addvspace"
@Prev "\appendix"
@Toc "Commands"

Spaces & Boxes
==============


 @{" \addvspace " Link "\addvspace"} 
 @{" \bigskip " Link "\bigskip"} 
 @{" \dotfill " Link "\dotfill"} 
 @{" \fbox " Link "\fbox"} 
 @{" \framebox " Link "\framebox"} 
 @{" \hfill " Link "\hfill"} 
 @{" \hrulefill " Link "\hrulefill"} 
 @{" \hspace " Link "\hspace"} 
 @{" \makebox " Link "\makebox"} 
 @{" \mbox " Link "\mbox"} 
 @{" \medskip " Link "\medskip"} 
 @{" \newsavebox " Link "\newsavebox"} 
 @{" \parbox " Link "\parbox"} 
 @{" \raisebox " Link "\raisebox"} 
 @{" \rule " Link "\rule"} 
 @{" \savebox " Link "\savebox"} 
 @{" \smallskip " Link "\smallskip"} 
 @{" \usebox " Link "\usebox"} 
 @{" \vfill " Link "\vfill"} 
 @{" \vspace " Link "\vspace"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\addvspace" "latex.guide/\addvspace"
@Next "\bigskip"
@Prev "Spaces & Boxes"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\addvspace
----------

   @{b}\addvspace{length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\addvspace@{ub} command normally adds a vertical space of height
length.  However, if vertical space has already been added to the same
point in the output by a previous @{b}\addvspace@{ub} command, then this command
will not add more space than needed to make the natural length of the
total vertical space equal to @{b}length@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\bigskip" "latex.guide/\bigskip"
@Next "\dotfill"
@Prev "\addvspace"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\bigskip
--------

   The @{b}\bigskip@{ub} command is equivalent to @{b}\vspace{bigskipamount}@{ub} where
@{b}bigskipamount@{ub} is determined by the document style.


@EndNode

@Node "\dotfill" "latex.guide/\dotfill"
@Next "\fbox"
@Prev "\bigskip"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\dotfill
--------

   The @{b}\dotfill@{ub} command produces a "rubber length" that produces dots
instead of just spaces.


@EndNode

@Node "\fbox" "latex.guide/\fbox"
@Next "\framebox"
@Prev "\dotfill"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\fbox
-----

   @{b}\fbox{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\fbox@{ub} command is exactly the same as the @{b}\mbox@{ub} command, except
that it puts a frame around the outside of the box that it creates.


@EndNode

@Node "\framebox" "latex.guide/\framebox"
@Next "\hfill"
@Prev "\fbox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\framebox
---------

   @{b}\framebox[width][position]{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\framebox@{ub} command is exactly the same as the @{b}\makebox@{ub} command,
except that it puts a frame around the outside of the box that it
creates.

   The framebox command produces a rule of thickness @{b}\fboxrule@{ub}, and
leaves a space @{b}\fboxsep@{ub} between the rule and the contents of the box.


@EndNode

@Node "\hfill" "latex.guide/\hfill"
@Next "\hrulefill"
@Prev "\framebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\hfill
------

   The @{b}\hfill@{ub} fill command produces a "rubber length" which can stretch
or shrink horizontally.  It will be filled with spaces.


@EndNode

@Node "\hrulefill" "latex.guide/\hrulefill"
@Next "\hspace"
@Prev "\hfill"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\hrulespace
-----------

   The @{b}\hrulefill@{ub} fill command produces a "rubber length" which can
stretch or shrink horizontally.  It will be filled with a horizontal
rule.


@EndNode

@Node "\hspace" "latex.guide/\hspace"
@Next "\makebox"
@Prev "\hrulefill"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\hspace
-------

   @{b}\hspace[*]{length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\hspace@{ub} command adds horizontal space.  The length of the space
can be expressed in any terms that LaTeX understands, i.e., points,
inches, etc.  You can add negative as well as positive space with an
@{b}\hspace@{ub} command.  Adding negative space is like backspacing.

   LaTeX removes horizontal space that comes at the end of a line.  If
you don't want LaTeX to remove this space, include the optional @{b}*@{ub}
argument.  Then the space is never removed.


@EndNode

@Node "\makebox" "latex.guide/\makebox"
@Next "\mbox"
@Prev "\hspace"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\makebox
--------

   @{b}\makebox[width][position]{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\makebox@{ub} command creates a box just wide enough to contain the
@{b}text@{ub} specified.  The width of the box is specified by the optional
@{b}width@{ub} argument.  The position of the text within the box is
determined by the optional @{b}position@{ub} argument.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}c@{ub} - centered (default)

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}l@{ub} - flushleft

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}r@{ub} - flushright

   See @{"\makebox (picture)" Link "\makebox (picture)"}.


@EndNode

@Node "\mbox" "latex.guide/\mbox"
@Next "\medskip"
@Prev "\makebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\mbox
-----

   @{b}\mbox{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\mbox@{ub} command creates a box just wide enough to hold the text
created by its argument.


@EndNode

@Node "\medskip" "latex.guide/\medskip"
@Next "\newsavebox"
@Prev "\mbox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\medskip
--------

   The @{b}\medskip@{ub} command is equivalent to @{b}\vspace{medskipamount}@{ub} where
@{b}medskipamount@{ub} is determined by the document style.


@EndNode

@Node "\newsavebox" "latex.guide/\newsavebox"
@Next "\parbox"
@Prev "\medskip"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\newsavebox
-----------

   @{b}\newsavebox{cmd}@{ub}

   Declares @{b}cmd@{ub}, which must be a command name that is not already
defined, to be a bin for saving boxes.


@EndNode

@Node "\parbox" "latex.guide/\parbox"
@Next "\raisebox"
@Prev "\newsavebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\parbox
-------

   @{b}\parbox[position]{width}{text}@{ub}

   A @{b}parbox@{ub} is a box whose contents are created in @{b}paragraph@{ub} mode.  The
@{b}\parbox@{ub} has two mandatory arguments:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}width@{ub} - specifies the width of the parbox, and

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}text@{ub} - the text that goes inside the parbox.

   LaTeX will position a @{b}parbox@{ub} so its center lines up with the center
of the text line.  An optional first argument, @{b}position@{ub}, allows you to
line up either the top or bottom line in the parbox.

   A @{b}\parbox@{ub} command is used for a parbox containing a small piece of
text, with nothing fancy inside.  In particular, you shouldn't use any
of the paragraph-making environments inside a @{b}\parbox@{ub} argument.  For
larger pieces of text, including ones containing a paragraph-making
environment, you should use a @{b}minipage@{ub} environment.


@EndNode

@Node "\raisebox" "latex.guide/\raisebox"
@Next "\rule"
@Prev "\parbox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\raisebox
---------

   @{b}\raisebox{distance}[extend-above][extend-below]{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\raisebox@{ub} command is used to raise or lower text.  The first
mandatory argument specifies how high the text is to be raised (or
lowered if it is a negative amount).  The text itself is processed in
@{b}LR mode@{ub}.

   Sometimes it's useful to make LaTeX think something has a different
size than it really does - or a different size than LaTeX would normally
think it has.  The @{b}\raisebox@{ub} command lets you tell LaTeX how tall it is.

   The first optional argument, @{b}extend-above@{ub}, makes LaTeX think that
the text extends above the line by the amount specified.  The second
optional argument, @{b}extend-below@{ub}, makes LaTeX think that the text
extends below the line by the amount specified.


@EndNode

@Node "\rule" "latex.guide/\rule"
@Next "\savebox"
@Prev "\raisebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\rule
-----

   @{b}\rule[raise-height]{width}{thickness}@{ub}

   The @{b}\rule@{ub} command is used to produce horizontal lines.  The
arguments are defined as follows:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}raise-height@{ub} - specifies how high to raise the rule (optional)

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}width@{ub} - specifies the length of the rule (mandatory)

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}thickness@{ub} - specifies the thickness of the rule (mandatory)


@EndNode

@Node "\savebox" "latex.guide/\savebox"
@Next "\smallskip"
@Prev "\rule"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\savebox
--------

      \sbox{cmd}[text]
      \savebox{cmd}[width][pos]{text}

   These commands typeset @{b}text@{ub} in a box just as for @{b}\mbox@{ub} or @{b}\makebox@{ub}.
However, instead of printing the resulting box, they save it in bin
@{b}cmd@{ub}, which must have been declared with @{b}\newsavebox@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "\smallskip" "latex.guide/\smallskip"
@Next "\usebox"
@Prev "\savebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\smallskip
----------

   @{b}\smallskip@{ub}

   The @{b}\smallskip@{ub} command is equivalent to @{b}\vspace{smallskipamount}@{ub}
where @{b}smallskipamount@{ub} is determined by the document style.


@EndNode

@Node "\usebox" "latex.guide/\usebox"
@Next "\vfill"
@Prev "\smallskip"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\usebox
-------

   @{b}\usebox{cmd}@{ub}

   Prints the box most recently saved in bin @{b}cmd@{ub} by a @{b}\savebox@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "\vfill" "latex.guide/\vfill"
@Next "\vspace"
@Prev "\usebox"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\vfill
------

   The @{b}\vfill@{ub} fill command produces a rubber length which can stretch
or shrink vertically.


@EndNode

@Node "\vspace" "latex.guide/\vspace"
@Next "Special Characters"
@Prev "\vfill"
@Toc "Spaces & Boxes"

\vspace
-------

   @{b}\vspace[*]{length}@{ub}

   The @{b}\vspace@{ub} command adds vertical space.  The length of the space
can be expressed in any terms that LaTeX understands, i.e., points,
inches, etc.  You can add negative as well as positive space with an
@{b}\vspace@{ub} command.

   LaTeX removes vertical space that comes at the end of a page.  If you
don't want LaTeX to remove this space, include the optional @{b}*@{ub} argument.
Then the space is never removed.


@EndNode

@Node "Special Characters" "latex.guide/Special Characters"
@Next "Splitting the Input"
@Prev "\vspace"
@Toc "Commands"

Special Characters
==================

   The following characters play a special role in LaTeX and are called
"special printing characters", or simply "special characters".

                               # $ % & ~ _ ^ \ { }
   Whenever you put one of these special characters into your file, you
are doing something special.  If you simply want the character to be
printed just as any other letter, include a @{b}\ @{ub} in front of the
character.  For example, @{b}\$@{ub} will produce @{b}$@{ub} in your output.

   The exception to the rule is the @{b}\ @{ub} itself because @{b}\\ @{ub} has its own
special meaning.  A @{b}\ @{ub} is produced by typing @{b}$\backslash$@{ub} in your file.


@EndNode

@Node "Splitting the Input" "latex.guide/Splitting the Input"
@Next "\include"
@Prev "Special Characters"
@Toc "Commands"

Splitting the Input
===================

   A large document requires a lot of input.  Rather than putting the
whole input in a single large file, it's more efficient to split it into
several smaller ones.  Regardless of how many separate files you use,
there is one that is the root file; it is the one whose name you type
when you run LaTeX.


 @{" \include " Link "\include"} 
 @{" \includeonly " Link "\includeonly"} 
 @{" \input " Link "\input"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\include" "latex.guide/\include"
@Next "\includeonly"
@Prev "Splitting the Input"
@Toc "Splitting the Input"

\include
--------

   @{b}\include{file}@{ub}

   The @{b}\include@{ub} command is used in conjunction with the @{b}\includeonly@{ub}
command for selective inclusion of files.  The @{b}file@{ub} argument is the
first name of a file, denoting @{b}file.tex@{ub}.  If @{b}file@{ub} is one the file names
in the file list of the @{b}\includeonly@{ub} command or if there is no
@{b}\includeonly@{ub} command, the @{b}\include@{ub} command is equivalent to
     \clearpage \input{file} \clearpage
   except that if the file @{b}file.tex@{ub} does not exist, then a warning
message rather than an error is produced.  If the file is not in the
file list, the @{b}\include@{ub} command is equivalent to @{b}\clearpage@{ub}.

   The @{b}\include@{ub} command may not appear in the preamble or in a file
read by another @{b}\include@{ub} command.


@EndNode

@Node "\includeonly" "latex.guide/\includeonly"
@Next "\input"
@Prev "\include"
@Toc "Splitting the Input"

\includeonly
------------

   @{b}\includeonly{file_list}@{ub}

   The @{b}\includeonly@{ub} command controls which files will be read in by an
@{b}\include@{ub} command.  It can only appear in the preamble.


@EndNode

@Node "\input" "latex.guide/\input"
@Next "Starting & Ending"
@Prev "\includeonly"
@Toc "Splitting the Input"

\input
------

   @{b}\input{file}@{ub}

   The @{b}\input@{ub} command causes the indicated @{b}file@{ub} to be read and
processed, exactly as if its contents had been inserted in the current
file at that point.  The file name may be a complete file name with
extension or just a first name, in which case the file @{b}file.tex@{ub} is used.


@EndNode

@Node "Starting & Ending" "latex.guide/Starting & Ending"
@Next "Table of Contents"
@Prev "\input"
@Toc "Commands"

Starting & Ending
=================

   Your input file must contain the following commands as a minimum...

      \documentstyle{style}
      \begin{document}
        ... your text goes here ...
      \end{document}
   ...where the @{b}style@{ub} selected is one the valid styles for LaTeX.  See
@{"Document Styles" Link "Document Styles"}, and also see @{"Overview" Link "Overview"}, for details of the various
document styles available locally.

   You may include other LaTeX commands between the @{b}\documentstyle@{ub} and
the @{b}\begin{document}@{ub} commands.


@EndNode

@Node "Table of Contents" "latex.guide/Table of Contents"
@Next "\addcontentsline"
@Prev "Starting & Ending"
@Toc "Commands"

Table of Contents
=================

   A table of contents is produced with the @{b}\tableofcontents@{ub} command.
You put the command right where you want the table of contents to go;
LaTeX does the rest for you.  It produces a heading, but it does not
automatically start a new page.  If you want a new page after the table
of contents, include a @{b}\newpage@{ub} command after the @{b}\tableofcontents@{ub}
command.

   There are similar commands @{b}\listoffigures@{ub} and @{b}\listoftables@{ub} for
producing a list of figures and a list of tables, respectively.
Everything works exactly the same as for the table of contents.

   NOTE: If you want any of these  items  to be generated,  you cannot
have the @{b}\nofiles@{ub} command in your document.


 @{" \addcontentsline " Link "\addcontentsline"} 
 @{" \addtocontents " Link "\addtocontents"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\addcontentsline" "latex.guide/\addcontentsline"
@Next "\addtocontents"
@Prev "Table of Contents"
@Toc "Table of Contents"

\addcontentsline
----------------

   @{b}\addcontentsline{file}{sec_unit}{entry}@{ub}

   The @{b}\addcontentsline@{ub} command adds an entry to the specified list or
table where...

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}file@{ub} is the extension of the file on which information is to be
     written: @{b}toc@{ub} (table of contents), @{b}lof@{ub} (list of figures), or @{b}lot@{ub}
     (list of tables).

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}sec_unit@{ub} controls the formatting of the entry.  It should be
     one of the following, depending upon the value of the file
     argument:
       1.     @{b}toc@{ub} - the name of the sectional unit, such as part or
          subsection.

       2.     @{b}lof@{ub} - figure

       3.     @{b}lot@{ub} - table

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}entry@{ub} is the text of the entry.


@EndNode

@Node "\addtocontents" "latex.guide/\addtocontents"
@Next "Terminal Input/Output"
@Prev "\addcontentsline"
@Toc "Table of Contents"

\addtocontents
--------------

   @{b}\addtocontents{file}{text}@{ub}

   The @{b}\addtocontents@{ub} command adds text (or formatting commands)
directly to the file that generates the table of contents or list of
figures or tables.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}file@{ub} is the extension of the file on which information is to be
     written: @{b}toc@{ub} (table of contents), @{b}lof@{ub} (list of figures), or @{b}lot@{ub}
     (list of tables).

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}text@{ub} is the information to be written.


@EndNode

@Node "Terminal Input/Output" "latex.guide/Terminal Input/Output"
@Next "\typeout"
@Prev "\addtocontents"
@Toc "Commands"

Terminal Input/Output
=====================


 @{" \typeout " Link "\typeout"} 
 @{" \typein " Link "\typein"} 


@EndNode

@Node "\typeout" "latex.guide/\typeout"
@Next "\typein"
@Prev "Terminal Input/Output"
@Toc "Terminal Input/Output"

\typeout
--------

   @{b}\typeout{msg}@{ub}

   Prints @{b}msg@{ub} on the terminal and in the @{b}log@{ub} file.  Commands in @{b}msg@{ub}
that are defined with @{b}\newcommand@{ub} or @{b}\renewcommand@{ub} are replaced by
their definitions before being printed.

   LaTeX's usual rules for treating multiple spaces as a single space
and ignoring spaces after a command name apply to @{b}msg@{ub}.  A @{b}\space@{ub}
command in @{b}msg@{ub} causes a single space to be printed.


@EndNode

@Node "\typein" "latex.guide/\typein"
@Next "Typefaces"
@Prev "\typeout"
@Toc "Terminal Input/Output"

\typein
-------

   @{b}\typein[cmd]{msg}@{ub}

   Prints @{b}msg@{ub} on the terminal and causes LaTeX to stop and wait for you
to type a line of input, ending with return.  If the @{b}cmd@{ub} argument is
missing, the typed input is processed as if it had been included in the
input file in place of the @{b}\typein@{ub} command.  If the @{b}cmd@{ub} argument is
present, it must be a command name.  This command name is then defined
or redefined to be the typed input.


@EndNode

@Node "Typefaces" "latex.guide/Typefaces"
@Next "Styles"
@Prev "\typein"
@Toc "Commands"

Typefaces
=========

   The @{b}typeface@{ub} is specified by giving the "size" and "style".  A
typeface is also called a "font".


 @{" Styles " Link "Styles"} 
 @{" Sizes " Link "Sizes"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Styles" "latex.guide/Styles"
@Next "Sizes"
@Prev "Typefaces"
@Toc "Typefaces"

\Styles
-------

   The following type style commands are supported by LaTeX.

@{b}\rm@{ub}
     Roman.

@{b}\it@{ub}
     Italics.

@{b}\em@{ub}
     Emphasis (toggles between \it and \rm).

@{b}\bf@{ub}
     Boldface.

@{b}\sl@{ub}
     Slanted.

@{b}\sf@{ub}
     Sans serif.

@{b}\sc@{ub}
     Small caps.

@{b}\tt@{ub}
     Typewriter.


@EndNode

@Node "Sizes" "latex.guide/Sizes"
@Next "Parameters"
@Prev "Styles"
@Toc "Typefaces"

Sizes
-----

   The following type size commands are supported by LaTeX.

@{b}\tiny@{ub}
@{b}\scriptsize@{ub}
@{b}\footnotesize@{ub}
@{b}\small@{ub}
@{b}\normalsize@{ub}
     (default)

@{b}\large@{ub}
@{b}\Large@{ub}
     (capital "l")

@{b}\LARGE@{ub}
     (all caps)

@{b}\huge@{ub}
@{b}\Huge@{ub}
     (capital "h")


@EndNode

@Node "Parameters" "latex.guide/Parameters"
@Next "List of Commands"
@Prev "Sizes"
@Toc "Main"

Parameters
**********

   The input file specification indicates the file to be formatted; TeX
uses @{b}.tex@{ub} as a default file extension.  If you omit the input file
entirely, TeX accepts input from the terminal.  You specify command
options by supplying a string as a parameter to the command. eg.

   @{b}latex "\scrollmode\input foo.tex"@{ub}

   ...will process @{b}foo.tex@{ub} without pausing after every error.

   Output files are always created in the current directory. When you
fail to specify an input file name, TeX bases the output names on the
file specification associated with the logical name TEX_OUTPUT,
typically @{b}texput.log@{ub}.


@EndNode

